 {"id":"bd-1x6","title":"Implement rich health check event formatting","description":"# Implement Rich Health Check Event Formatting

## What
Format health check results with colored status indicators when checks pass, slow, or fail.

## Current Output (Plain)
Health checks logged via tracing:
```
INFO health check passed for mesh-us (42ms)
WARN health check slow for mesh-us (890ms)
ERROR health check failed for mesh-us: timeout
```

## New Output (Rich)
```
[14:35:00] ✓ Health check passed (mesh-us, 42ms)
[14:35:30] ⚠ Health check slow (mesh-us, 890ms)
[14:36:00] ✗ Health check failed (mesh-us, timeout)
```

## Why This Design
- Symbols (✓/⚠/✗) provide instant visual status
- Colors reinforce meaning (green/yellow/red)
- Timestamp for correlation
- Proxy name identifies which proxy
- Latency or error reason in parentheses

## Status Categories

### Passed (Green ✓)
- Check completed within timeout
- Latency < threshold (e.g., 500ms)
- Show: latency in ms

### Slow (Yellow ⚠)
- Check completed but latency > threshold
- Show: latency in ms with warning

### Failed (Red ✗)
- Check timed out or connection refused
- Show: error reason (timeout, connection refused, etc.)

## Format Implementation

```rust
fn format_health_check_event(
    proxy_name: &str,
    result: &HealthCheckResult,
    threshold_ms: u64
) -> String {
    let timestamp = Utc::now().format("%H:%M:%S");

    match result {
        HealthCheckResult::Ok(latency_ms) if *latency_ms < threshold_ms => {
            format!(
                "[bright_black][{}][/] [green]✓[/] Health check passed ({}, {}ms)",
                timestamp, proxy_name, latency_ms
            )
        }
        HealthCheckResult::Ok(latency_ms) => {
            format!(
                "[bright_black][{}][/] [yellow]⚠[/] Health check slow ({}, {}ms)",
                timestamp, proxy_name, latency_ms
            )
        }
        HealthCheckResult::Failed(reason) => {
            format!(
                "[bright_black][{}][/] [red]✗[/] Health check failed ({}, {})",
                timestamp, proxy_name, reason
            )
        }
    }
}
```

## Slow Threshold
- Default: 500ms
- Could be configurable
- Anything > threshold but < timeout is "slow"

## Verbose vs Quiet
- Default: Only show slow and failed
- --verbose: Show all checks including passed
- This reduces noise during normal operation

## Integration with Tracing
Health check events could be:
- Printed via OutputDispatcher (rich output)
- AND logged via tracing (for log files)

Tracing output should be plain for machine parsing:
```rust
tracing::info!(proxy = %name, latency_ms = %ms, "health check passed");
tracing::warn!(proxy = %name, latency_ms = %ms, "health check slow");
tracing::error!(proxy = %name, reason = %r, "health check failed");
```

## Machine Mode
In Machine mode:
- No rich output
- Only tracing logs

## Edge Cases
- Multiple proxies: Each gets its own line
- Rapid failures: May flood output (consider rate limiting)
- First check: May take longer, don't warn

## Files Modified
- src/health.rs (add rich formatting)
- src/main.rs (wire up to OutputDispatcher)

## Verification
- Run daemon with health checks enabled
- Verify passed checks show green ✓
- Simulate slow response, verify yellow ⚠
- Simulate failure, verify red ✗","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-01-19T21:09:44.073491578Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-01-19T21:28:31.061722037Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["daemon","rich-integration"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-1x6","depends_on_id":"bd-1ke","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-01-19T21:09:44.100875687Z","created_by":"ubuntu"},{"issue_id":"bd-1x6","depends_on_id":"bd-s0h","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-01-19T21:28:31.061678705Z","created_by":"ubuntu"},{"issue_id":"bd-1x6","depends_on_id":"bd-thy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-01-19T21:10:04.935981434Z","created_by":"ubuntu"}]}
 {"id":"bd-23j","title":"Update 'deactivate' command with rich confirmation","description":"# Update 'deactivate' Command with Rich Confirmation

## What
Show confirmation when proxy is deactivated, noting firewall cleanup status.

## Current Output (Plain)
```
Deactivated proxy
Cleared iptables rules
Destroyed ipset
```

## New Output (Rich)
```
✓ Deactivated proxy mesh-us

┌─ Cleanup Status ────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ ✓ Removed iptables NAT rules                                │
│ ✓ Destroyed ipset 'rust_proxy_targets'                      │
│ ✓ Traffic now routes directly                               │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Why This Design
- Confirms which proxy was deactivated
- Panel shows firewall cleanup status
- Each cleanup step shown for transparency
- Final note confirms traffic behavior changed

## Cleanup Steps
1. Remove iptables NAT rules (RUST_PROXY chain)
2. Destroy ipset (rust_proxy_targets)
3. Note: Traffic now routes directly

## With --keep-rules Flag
```
✓ Deactivated proxy mesh-us

  Firewall rules retained (--keep-rules)
  Traffic will continue routing through proxy until daemon restarts
```

## Non-Root Execution
If run without root, cannot clean firewall:
```
✓ Deactivated proxy mesh-us

⚠ Firewall rules NOT cleaned (requires root)
  Run 'sudo rust_proxy deactivate' to remove iptables/ipset rules
```

## Edge Cases
- --json: JSON output
- No active proxy: Info panel "No proxy is currently active"
- Non-root: Warning about firewall rules
- --keep-rules: Note rules retained

## Files Modified
- src/main.rs (cmd_deactivate function)

